 HN6[
] The grant of power to the FCC to enforce various provisions of the Clayton Act is not exclusive. In addition to the 
Commission's administrative jurisdiction, judicial jurisdiction may be exercised by federal district courts and invoked either by the 
government or by private individuals. See U.S. v. W.T. Grant Co., 345 U.S. 629, 631-32, 97 L. Ed. 1303, 73 S. Ct. 894 (1953); 
FTC v. Int'l Paper Co., 241 F.2d 372 (2 Cir. 1956).

 HN17[
] A state is a "person" entitled to sue for damages and injunctive relief under the Act, 15 U.S.C. 15 (1964). See Georgia v. Evans, 316 U.S. 159, 86 L. Ed. 1346, 62 S. Ct. 972 (1942); Hawaii v. Standard Oil Co., 405 U.S. 251, 261, 31 L. Ed. 
2d 184, 92 S. Ct. 885 (1972).

